"In the immediate aftermath of any data security incident, the attention of a company's management will inevitably swing quickly towards trying to seek appropriate legal redress and compensation for the damages an entity has suffered and the costs it has incurred in responding to that security incident. Invariably, such an incident will have had a major impact on the company, both in terms of the required engagement of internal and external stakeholders in the business and this will have come at a cost. Indeed, it would only be natural to want to recover some of these losses. In the immediate aftermath of any data security incident, the attention of a company's management will inevitably swing quickly towards trying to seek appropriate legal redress and compensation. It's natural to want to recover some of your losses, but such a response can frequently descend into a frustrating experience. However, with some very careful planning prior to any data security incident, a well-prepared company can incorporate a potential litigation strategy into its data security incident response plan, explains Mark Deem of Cooley (UK) LLP."
